# .dockerignore — keep the Docker build context small and
# deterministic.
#
# Without this, `docker build .` would tar up the entire
# app_root/ directory (including the multi-hundred-MB .venv
# and the on-disk NiceGUI storage cache) every build. The
# Dockerfile's `COPY` lines would then have to explicitly
# skip them, which is error-prone.
#
# Patterns use Git's wildcards (Docker's build context builder
# is just a tar over the working tree, so the same semantics
# apply). One pattern per line; blank lines are ignored.
#
# Mirrors .gitignore but with three deliberate differences:
#   * `!.dockerignore` itself is not in here (no point)
#   * `!requirements.txt` is forced include (already added)
#   * `app_root/tests/` is included — the image is a
#     *runtime* image so we don't need the tests, but the
#     Dockerfile explicitly `COPY`s only the directories it
#     needs, so the test dir never makes it in regardless.

# Virtualenv — heaviest single dir; never useful in an image
.venv/
venv/
env/

# Caches & build artefacts
.nicegui/
.pytest_cache/
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.pyd

# IDE / editor cruft
.idea/
.vscode/
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# Git metadata
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# Tests — runtime image doesn't need them
tests/

# CI — workflows are useful as reference but not at runtime
.github/

# Docs — the static export lives in docs/ at build time, but
# not in the runtime image
docs/

# Logs and runtime data
logs/
*.log

# The Dockerfile copies only the directories it needs, but
# .dockerignore's "deny first" semantic means we have to
# explicitly re-allow a few files that would otherwise be
# caught by a wider pattern (none today, but the hook is
# here for future patterns).
!README.md
!requirements.txt
